This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it focuses on the task of pedestrian detection using convolutional neural networks. The paper also discusses various architectural choices and parameters of the convnets, which suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of pre-training on surrogate tasks, which is a common technique in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The fact that the paper is focused on pedestrian detection suggests that it may also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category, as this is a common task in robotics research. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of the convnet detectors, which suggests that it may also belong to the cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-category, as performance is often a key concern in security-related applications.
